Some people say that the main aim of advertising is to improve the sales of products that people do not really need. To what extend, do you agree or disagree.

It is often argued that the primary aim of advertising is to boost sales by persuading consumers to purchase products they do not truly need. While I agree that advertising frequently creates demand for nonessential goods, I believe it also plays an important role in informing consumers and helping them make better purchasing decisions.

On the one hand, advertising can be highly effective in encouraging unnecessary consumption. This is largely due to the use of persuasive techniques that frame luxury items as essential to a desirable lifestyle. For example, advertisements often portray idealized lifestyles that evoke feelings of inadequacy, leading consumers to buy products in an attempt to improve their self-image. In addition, time-limited promotions, such as flash sales or exclusive deals, create a sense of urgency that drives impulse buying. As a result, people may spend money on items they neither planned to buy nor genuinely need.

On the other hand, advertising also provides valuable information that helps consumers make informed choices. Many advertisements highlight key features, comparisons, and practical benefits, allowing buyers to evaluate whether a product suits their needs. For instance, commercials for electronic devices often compare battery life, performance, and price, enabling consumers to select the most appropriate option. Furthermore, certain campaigns—particularly those related to health or public awareness—can educate the public about important issues and beneficial products. In this way, advertising can align commercial interests with genuine consumer needs.

In conclusion, although advertising undeniably encourages the consumption of unnecessary products through emotional appeal and strategic marketing, it also serves a useful informational purpose. Therefore, I partly agree with the view that its main aim is to increase sales of unneeded goods, but I believe its overall role is more complex and not entirely negative.
